commentBody:
@Barry Ancona

No link on the Crossword page at 7:50 am EDT, and when I went to yesterday's Wordplay and changed the date, I got a "Page Not Found" message.

Finally found my way here with Google.

@PB
Same. Both Games app as well as NYT News app. It’s awful and seems to be getting worse daily. 

Games app -22x in 13 minutes.

@Steve L

What’s a desktop? ; - )

Wow, that emoji is a pain to do on a phone. That’s why you need a desktop.

@SP and jennie,

I don't drink them dirty, but I'll raise my martini glass, as well! (Even if I am a Gopher now!)

I did see that Gov Evers declared June 30 as WI Kringle Day, so though I love my transplant home, that is the thing that might lure me back down there....  har!  My fam and friends who are still there aren't impressed that it would take Kringle to make me come back.  😏

@Jennie @HeathieJ @SP et al.

I'll see your ale glass and raise you a spoon of Babcock Hall ice cream! Go Badgers!

And Heathie, in case you don't know, Trader Joe's carries real Racine kringle four times a year (I think Nov. Feb. May Aug.), a different flavor each time. They won't tell you when it comes in, you just have to keep an eye out. I usually buy three or four and freeze some. During the last war the US won Mom was a young Rosie the riveter making tanks at Massey-Harris in Racine while her brothers were overseas fighting. We had kringle at most holidays. A different time to say the least.

@Cat Lady Margaret

People believe that sleep velocity is the relevant statistic, but studies have shown that sleep momentum is what truly counts in determining your NQR (Nap Quality Ratio).

Of course, there are those new narcometric specialists who try to argue that we shouldn't be talking about SQR at all, but examine ECH (Eyes Closed Horizontality):  the number of hours one spends in a horizontal state times the number of hours one spends with one's eyes closed, but I think they're way out in left field in terms of this analysis.  They don't even consider the bed vs. couch question.

@RL
Here at a reasonable hour, for the first time in ages. Yay!
I got ADOUT entirely via crossings, and a good thing too.  Tennis terms are like Urdu to me. That said, I'd say the question mark at clue's end is a sufficient warning that Something was Up in 38A!

@Steve L
I loved the shoutout to budgerigars.
Respect.

@Dorothy

Tennis-ese.

ADOUT = "advantage out" = advantage to the player not serving

@Petrol

My experience,
nearly to the letter!

@Vaer
Thought you wouldn't see my response to you last night about seeing my comment in a puzzle from 2016, so here it is again: 

I don't know why it would have said NJ in 2016. For several years, beginning in 2004, I was back and forth between NJ and Vegas, not exactly as a snowbird, just three months at a time in each place. But I became a permanent resident of Vegas in 2007, and considered myself as a bona fide Vegas resident, even though I was still going back and forth, although for less time in NJ, until the pandemic hit. Now that my daughter and grandson are here and that house is gone, NJ and NY are just a memory, except that's where all my dearest friends live.

@Bill
Noted. 
BTW, my brain has me singing I'm so MADS to the opening of Cream's version of I'm So Glad.

@D
I actually did use the theme today--once I realized there were two words beginning with M and T I was able to go to the themers and plug them in.

In other news, IONIA  is one of those pieces of glue that keeps coming back because all the vowels make it useful. As someone joked elsewhere, we had IONE yesterday and IONIA today; they wondered if tomorrow will bring IONA. Personally I'm hoping for IONIAN.

@Lori Petrie

I appears that a lot of people are having similar problems.  I would imagine the NYT is aware of it, but you could also write to NYT at <a href="mailto:NYTGames@nytimes.com">NYTGames@nytimes.com</a>.  

Good luck.

@Doug
It is a truth universally acknowledged that the solving of problem A will result in the introduction of problem B.
Or as we used to say in our family: There are no solutions but you do have your choice of problems.

@HeathieJ

You can solve from the browser on your phone or tablet, too. 

(I just don’t care that much for the interface on Safari, so I do use the app when I’m using the phone, and I haven’t experienced any problems recently.)

@Steve L

That's true, and I guess I have done that in my earlier days when I wasn't sure if I wanted the app yet or not. I agree that the interface on the app is better than the phone browser. 

But this is a good reminder for if I did jinx myself and my app stops working!  ☺️

@Francisco Zappa Thank you to the tech team on getting this sorted out. 

I do ~ 6-8 crosswords from the archive each day. FWIW, I’m working backwards in time. Started on Mondays, then Tues, then Weds; now I’m midway through Thursdays. For the last 2 years I’ve been a 7-day a week player as well. 
I’m a rookie I’m sure lol. 🥂
